<definition>
The <term>expected value</term> of a game of chance is the average net gain or loss that we would expect per game if we played the game many times. We compute the expected value by multiplying the value of each outcome by its probability of occurring and then adding up all of the products.
</definition>

<p>For example, imagine you have a coin that comes up heads <m>1/4</m> of the time and tails <m>3/4</m> of the time. If you gain <m>2</m> dollars for every heads and lose <m>4</m> dollars for every tails, the expected value of the game is <me>(\frac{1}{4}*2) + (\frac{3}{4} * -4) =\frac{1}{2} -3 = -\frac{5}{2} </me></p>

