<p>Recall that the expected value of a game <m>A</m> with strategies <m>\textbf{p}</m> and <m>\textbf{q}</m> for Rose and Colin respectively can be calculated as <m>\textbf{p}A\textbf{q}</m>.</p>

<theorem>
Let <m>\textbf{p}</m> and <m>\textbf{q}</m> be strategies for Rose and Colin in the zero sum matrix game <m>A</m>. Then
<ol>
  <li> If <m>\textbf{p}</m> has a guarantee of <m>r</m>, then <m>\textbf{p}A\textbf{q} \geq r</m>. </li>
  <li> If <m>\textbf{q}</m> has a guarantee of <m>c</m>, then <m>\textbf{p}A\textbf{q} \leq c</m>. </li>
  <li> If <m>\textbf{p}</m> and <m>\textbf{q}</m> have guarantees of <m>r</m> and <m>c</m>, then <m>r \leq c</m>. </li>
</ol>
</theorem>

